BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Stories from the Smithsonian Center for Folklife
DTSTART;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260326T173000
DTEND;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260326T183000
UID:260309ndJqjPCC006eYUDenbyvIg
DESCRIPTION:Oral Histories as Research and Cultural Democracy\n\nWhy do we
  tell our stories? Why listen to\, record\, archive\, and share the memori
 es of others? As part of the Making History\, Making Change Lecture Series
 \, Dr. Rebecca Fenton\, curator at the Smithsonian Center for Folklife and
  Cultural Heritage\, will explore how oral histories bring rich texture to
  our understanding of past events and traditions. Lifting up the narrators
 ' participation in cultural life\, oral histories reveal the many ways tha
 t all kinds of people shape their communities. For those inspired to recor
 d an oral history interview\, Dr. Fenton will also share resources and too
 ls for getting started in your family and community.\n\nThe Making History
 \, Making Change Lecture Series is a national collaboration between the Sm
 ithsonian and 25 Smithsonian Affiliate organizations\, featuring expert-le
 d talks that explore the people\, moments\, and ideals that have shaped—
 and continue to shape—the American experience.\n\nThe Making History\, M
 aking Change Lecture Series is organized by Smithsonian Affiliations as pa
 rt of the Smithsonian’s Our Shared Future: 250. It is supported in part 
 by the Dreier Family\, Johanna and Ken Kim Family\, Vaishali Shah Chadha a
 nd Family\, and Michael Vu & Meridel Bulle-Vu.\n\nLearn more: https://aff
 iliations.si.edu/making-history-making-change
LOCATION:Museum of Sonoma County
URL:https://museumsc.org/events/?eid=12851
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
