BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:"Standin' In a Hard Rain" Interview and Q&A with Author/Activist J
 oel Eis
DTSTART;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260326T183000
DTEND;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260326T200000
UID:260214QWXcN5U7EEmZI58ytYZWbA
DESCRIPTION:On Thursday March 26 at 6:30pm the San Geronimo Valley Commu
 nity Center's Valley Arts and Lectures Series will host author/activist Jo
 el Eis in conversation with Albert Flynn DeSilver. Eis claims to have beco
 me an activist “in utero” and his mothers refusal to cross a picket li
 ne when he was a child didn’t seem like a radical move\, it’s just how
  he was raised.  He often says his life's path was laid out\, often\, by 
 circumstances out of his own control. In his own words Eis says\, “Stand
 in' in a Hard Rain draws on my knack for being in the right place at the 
 right time. As a result of forces over which I had no control I was not on
 ly on the front lines and in the streets\, but in the room for planning so
 me of the major events of the 1960's.” \n\n Eis was present at many “
 inflection” points in the 60’s & 70’s. He was a part of the Freedom 
 Riders in the Deep South\, the Strike of '68 at S.F. State University \\(t
 he longest\, most violent student strike in American History\, the Draft R
 esistance with David Harris and Joan Baez\, the Grape Strike with Caesar C
 havez\, Angela Davis\, Eldridge Cleaver and the Panthers. He even faced a 
 bayonet at his own throat from the National Guard at Berkeley’s People
 ’s Park. He also used his training as an actor\, director\, and designer
  in important radical and progressive theatre companies for progressive ch
 ange. This put him in front of the crowd and backstage with the makers of 
 ideas.\n\nIn 2023\, after much encouragement from those who had been regal
 ed with his many stories\, he wrote his memoir “Standin’ in a Hard Ra
 in”. It turns out its release couldn’t have been more timely. I had t
 he thought that when he was writing his memoir\, Eis could not have imagin
 ed we would be where we are right now as a country …or maybe he did.   
 Although we are in unprecedented times\, there is a lot to be learned from
  this generation about what it takes to protect Civil Rights and Democracy
 . Please join us for this special event.
LOCATION:San Geronimo Valley Community Center
URL:https://sgvperformingarts.eventcalendarapp.com/interview-and-qanda-wit
 h-authoractivist-joel-eis
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Art Exhibit: Celebrating Women
DTSTART;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260326T110000
DTEND;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260326T180000
UID:260213Fw2D0iy4WU6Mk4hURkbJRA
DESCRIPTION:Date: FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE  2/13/26\n\n**MARCH EXHIBIT: CELE
 BRATING WOMEN**\n\nEXHIBIT DATES:  February 23 – March 29\, 2026\n\n**R
 ECEPTION: SATURDAY\, MARCH 7\, 2026\, 4-6 pm: Join in to meet the artists 
 and celebrate the show. Take part in the Gallery’s free monthly drawing 
 for a beautiful work by a Gallery artist.  Refreshments will be served.**
 \n\nSonoma County artist\, **Tosya Shore\,** presents **Celebrating Women\
 ,** paintings that commemorate women in honor of Women’s History Month. 
 Shore’s watercolor works capture women in their element\, showing the mu
 ltiple facets of their lives.  These dynamic paintings break away with st
 rong shapes and interlacing patterns that draw the viewer in exciting ways
 .  A la Degas\, we catch a ballet dancer lacing her shoes in “Good Poin
 t.”  The artist takes us into nature with “Redwood Rendezvous” wher
 e dominant trunk shapes frame a couple enjoying a glorious forest scene. 
    “Just Back from Vegas” captures a fleeting view of elegance as th
 e woman in question catches her breath.  “There’s such special feelin
 g in these everyday moments\, I love to turn the mundane into magic – wo
 men deserve nothing less\,” noted Shore. \n\nMeet the artist: Shore wil
 l be hosting the Gallery on March 5 and 19 from 11am to 6 pm.\n\n The Sta
 irway Smallworks Showcase features **Donna Schaffer’s Ooh La La\, Plein 
 Air\,** a collection unveiling oil paintings made on her recent trip to Fr
 ance.  Roaming the streets of Paris\, toting paints and palette\, Schaffe
 r captured iconic scenes buzzing with “la belle vie.” The viewer catch
 es a true cultural vibe in “Café le Bistro”\, the site of a favored h
 angout for espresso and conversation.  One is awed by the structure risin
 g from the ground-level trees in Schaffer’s unique view of the Eiffel To
 wer in “Paris is for Lovers.” “Every day was an adventure in Paris 
 – I hope through these plein air vignettes\, to share the excitement of 
 being there”\, stated Schaffer.\n\nMeet the artist: Schaffer will be hos
 ting the Gallery on March 21 and 22 from 11am to 6 pm.\n\nUpstairs Art Gal
 lery\, 306 Center Street\, Healdsburg\, CA 95448. (707) 431-4214.: OPEN DA
 ILY: 11am – 6 pm.    **www.upstairsart gallery.net** \n\nFor further 
 information: Contact: Beverly Bird\, Press Contact\, at bvdrio@sonic.net o
 r 707-799-1490.
LOCATION:Upstairs Art Gallery
URL:http://www.upstairsartgallery.net
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
