BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Eric Lindell & The Westside Summer League
DTSTART;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260328T200000
DTEND;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260328T000000
UID:260224UMX9jvfuwEG4NS5ijGdMjg
DESCRIPTION:Born in San Mateo\, California in 1969\, Lindell spent countle
 ss hours in San Francisco\, soaking up the musical sounds of the city\, ev
 entually leading him to pick up first the bass and then the guitar and har
 monica. With a love of music and skateboarding\, Lindell formed a few punk
 y garage bands early on while his musical horizons expanded. He listened t
 o the deep blues of Buddy Guy\, Junior Wells\, Jimmy Reed and Albert King 
 before drifting toward the R&B sounds of The Impressions\, Stevie Wonder a
 nd Donny Hathaway\, soaking up the soul and learning how to craft a song. 
 After performing at bars on the West Coast with a few short-lived bands\, 
 Eric formed his own group in 1993. He quickly gained a loyal Northern Cali
 fornia audience thanks to countless performances and many late-night jam s
 essions. Established stars like Charlie Musselwhite and Tom Waits attended
  his shows\, as did overflow crowds of music fans.\n\nWith music on his mi
 nd\, Lindell headed to New Orleans in 1999\, where he quickly discovered t
 he pulsating and dynamic roots scene. He gravitated toward the West Bank d
 ive bars of Gretna and Algiers\, where he befriended many older area music
 ians who helped him get regular work as a performer. Some of New Orleans' 
 finest players\, including keyboardist Ivan Neville and drummers Harold Br
 own \\(War\\)\, Stanton Moore \\(Galactic\\) and Johnny Vidacovich \\(Prof
 essor Longhair\, Astral Project\\) often joined him on stage. Galactic bas
 sist Rob Mercurio began sitting in as well\, and word of Lindell's immense
  talents quickly spread around the city. Stars like Branford Marsalis\, Th
 e Neville Brothers and John Scofield began showing up at his gigs and embr
 acing this fresh California kid's funky music. According to Lindell\, "It'
 s a great feeling to be recognized for your music in New Orleans." Since 2
 003\, in addition to his own gigs\, Lindell regularly joins forces with Iv
 an Neville\, Moore and Mercurio \\(when time and schedules permit\\) and t
 hey perform to overflow crowds as Dragon Smoke.\n\n2006's Change In The We
 ather delighted and surprised music fans hungry for a truly original artis
 t. Lindell's deceptively simple sounding songs\, laid back grooves and hoo
 k-laden melodies were fueled by guests including Brown\, Neville and Moore
 . Critics across the country went wild\, with reviews and features in Reli
 x\, OffBeat\, Guitar Player\, Down Beat\, The New Yorker\, The New York Pr
 ess and many other national and regional publications. Singer And Musician
  magazine put Eric on the cover and many newspaper entertainment sections 
 did the same.\n\n2007's Low On Cash\, Rich In Love and 2009's Gulf Coast H
 ighway pushed Lindell farther into the spotlight. Appearances on Late Nigh
 t With Conan O'Brien and National Public Radio's Mountain Stage solidified
  his stature as an artist who simply could not be ignored. Many of his son
 gs have appeared in films and television shows\, including Boston Legal an
 d Treme. He has collaborated and shared stages with blues and rock luminar
 ies\, including John Fogerty\, Luther Dickinson and Anson Funderburgh.\n\n
 With Revolution In Your Heart\, Lindell was more than ready to come home t
 o Alligator. "The timing is perfect. I'm so excited to get back to focusin
 g on what I do and have such a great team behind me\," he says. Upon relea
 se of the album\, Lindell and his band will tour heavily\, reuniting with 
 old friends and\, as always\, earning new fans at every stop. AllMusic dec
 lares Lindell a singular talent\, saying\, "He plays soulful\, funk-drench
 ed\, tight and focused grooves. He is a quadruple threat as a solid songwr
 iter\, impressive guitarist\, affecting singer and harmonica blower. This 
 is music that's deceptively difficult to create. Lindell makes it seem not
  just easy\, but natural."
LOCATION:The Elephant In the Room
URL:https://www.bandsintown.com/e/107833918?app_id=pkvts0on0m&came_from=28
 7&utm_medium=api&utm_source=partner_api&utm_campaign=event
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:T-Bone N Weasel - Live Theatre at THE 222 / Healdsburg
DTSTART;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260328T190000
DTEND;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260328T190000
UID:260219zxGiWUTwZk6ZE8ssgTWBUA
DESCRIPTION:**T**he play follows the antic peregrinations of two ex-convic
 ts as they make their erratic way across South Carolina in search of a hot
  meal or an easy mark.\n\nHoping to bring themselves up to at least the po
 verty level\, two ex-convicts\, T Bone (who is Black) and Weasel (who is W
 hite) have stolen a rather decrepit Buick and have set off across South Ca
 rolina with minor mayhem in mind. Moving swiftly from one adventure to an
 other\, they botch an attempted robbery\,  are swindled out of the Buick 
 by a fast-talking used car dealer\, run afoul of a sexually voracious lady
  farmer\, fall into the clutches of a larcenous country preacher\, and try
  to make off with the automobile of a politically ambitious small town doc
 tor who wants to exhibit them as examples of what poverty can do to people
 . Then it is back on the road again…\n\n*Every time they try to break th
 e law\, the law breaks them. A tale of two idiots\, smartly told by playwr
 ight Jon Klein\, “T-Bone n Weasel” is kind of like a good road-kill: i
 t’s funny\, gross and makes a lasting impression.* — Variety\n\nFeatur
 ing:\n\nT-Bone – Aldo Billingslea\n\nWeasel – Timothy Redman\n\nVerna 
 Mae – Sylvia Burboeck\n\n***Sponsored by Linda Hillel & Jon Eisenberg an
 d Malin Giddings & Richard Hechler***\n\nTheatre - Programmed by Aldo Bill
 ingslea and Amy Kossow\n\nTHE 222 / 222 Healdsburg Avenue / Healdsburg CA
LOCATION:THE 222 / Healdsburg
URL:https://the222.org/product/t-bone-n-weasel/
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Free Rowing Lessons in Classic Rowboats
DTSTART;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260328T100000
DTEND;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260328T110000
UID:260218nKfMq2cGT06LrA4hbDuSGA
DESCRIPTION:Have you ever wanted to learn the timeless—and beautiful—a
 rt of rowing? The Floathouse crew is here for you! This season\, every Sat
 urday from January 17 to March 28\, we’ll host free rowing lessons for a
 dults. Register online\, and we’ll take you through the basics in some o
 f our stable and beautiful rowing craft: the classic Whitehall rowboat\, t
 he classy Adirondack Guideboat\, and the cute but sturdy Captain’s Gig.\
 n\nNo experience necessary\, and no $$\, either. This is our gift to you.\
 n\nThis opportunity is available to all from January though March\, 2026. 
 Come once\, come every weekend\, or just now and then. Make this the year 
 you learn to row\, on Petaluma’s Longest Park\, the Petaluma River.\n\nR
 egister online\, and we’ll see you on the dock!
LOCATION:The Floathouse Petaluma
URL:https://www.thefloathousepetaluma.org/free-rowing-lessons
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Art Exhibit: Celebrating Women
DTSTART;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260328T110000
DTEND;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260328T180000
UID:260217bVkrJZHNBkaqNpTe9TIVZw
DESCRIPTION:Date: FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE  2/13/26\n\nMARCH EXHIBIT: CELEBR
 ATING WOMEN\n\nEXHIBIT DATES:  February 23 – March 29\, 2026\n\nRECEPTI
 ON: SATURDAY\, MARCH 7\, 2026\, 4-6 pm: Join in to meet the artists and ce
 lebrate the show. Take part in the Gallery’s free monthly drawing for a 
 beautiful work by a Gallery artist.  Refreshments will be served.\n\nSono
 ma County artist\, Tosya Shore\, presents Celebrating Women\, paintings th
 at commemorate women in honor of Women’s History Month. Shore’s waterc
 olor works capture women in their element\, showing the multiple facets of
  their lives.  These dynamic paintings break away with strong shapes and 
 interlacing patterns that draw the viewer in exciting ways.  A la Degas\,
  we catch a ballet dancer lacing her shoes in “Good Point.”  The arti
 st takes us into nature with “Redwood Rendezvous” where dominant trunk
  shapes frame a couple enjoying a glorious forest scene.    “Just Bac
 k from Vegas” captures a fleeting view of elegance as the woman in quest
 ion catches her breath.  “There’s such special feeling in these every
 day moments\, I love to turn the mundane into magic – women deserve noth
 ing less\,” noted Shore. \n\nMeet the artist: Shore will be hosting the
  Gallery on March 5 and 19 from 11am to 6 pm.\n\n The Stairway Smallworks
  Showcase features Donna Schaffer’s Ooh La La\, Plein Air\, a collection
  unveiling oil paintings made on her recent trip to France.  Roaming the 
 streets of Paris\, toting paints and palette\, Schaffer captured iconic sc
 enes buzzing with “la belle vie.” The viewer catches a true cultural v
 ibe in “Café le Bistro”\, the site of a favored hangout for espresso 
 and conversation.  One is awed by the structure rising from the ground-le
 vel trees in Schaffer’s unique view of the Eiffel Tower in “Paris is f
 or Lovers.” “Every day was an adventure in Paris – I hope through th
 ese plein air vignettes\, to share the excitement of being there”\, stat
 ed Schaffer.\n\nMeet the artist: Schaffer will be hosting the Gallery on M
 arch 21 and 22 from 11am to 6 pm.\n\nUpstairs Art Gallery\, 306 Center Str
 eet\, Healdsburg\, CA 95448. \\(707\\) 431-4214.: OPEN DAILY: 11am – 6 p
 m.    www.upstairsart gallery.net \n\nFor further information: Contact:
  Beverly Bird\, Press Contact\, at bvdrio@sonic.net or 707-799-1490.
LOCATION:Upstairs Art Gallery
URL:http://www.upstairsartgallery.net
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
