DESCRIPTION:In the vibrant music scene of Sonoma County\, this young band 
 born right here in Windsor\, California is making waves with their electri
 fying performances and undeniable talent. Formed by four teenagers\, Gas M
 oney has quickly become a local favorite\, captivating audiences with thei
 r unique blend of alternative rock and infectious energy. Showing that roc
 k and roll isn’t dead\, they play all your favorite tunes\, ranging from
  Stevie Wonder to Metallica\, ensuring a musical journey you won't forget.
 \n\nThe Band Members:\n\nCheyenne Vincent – Lead Vocals\n\nGavin Lee –
  Guitar and Vocals\n\nAlexander "AJ 18" Neujahr – Bass\n\nNick Carico - 
 Drums\n\nSince their humble beginnings in a living room in Windsor\, CA. G
 as Money has been on a mission to bring quality musical performances to ev
 ery show. Their music blends elements of 80s\, 90s\, and 2000s rock\, crea
 ting a nostalgic yet fresh experience for listeners of all ages. With perf
 ormances characterized by high energy\, tight musicianship\, and a genuine
  love for music that shines through\, Gas Money creates a sound that reson
 ates with audiences and leaves them craving more!
LOCATION:Coyote Sonoma
URL:https://www.pressdemocrat.com/events/#/details/gas-money/18242665/2026
 -04-03T20
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:"You're My Neighbor" Art Exhibit
DTSTART;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260403T090000
DTEND;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260403T180000
UID:260227oEwuwT8evU-6D2mwF0Bv8g
DESCRIPTION:Come out to Point Reyes and celebrate neighbors!   \n\nFrom 
 mooing cows and soaring birds to friendly faces down the road\, Cedars art
 ists take a joyful look at their Marin County neighborhood. This exhibitio
 n explores all the things that make their corner of the world special—op
 en fields\, wild creatures\, familiar people\, and the everyday moments in
  between. Through colorful\, thoughtful\, and imaginative works\, “You
 ’re My Neighbor” celebrates the beauty of living side by side and shar
 ing a place we call home.\n\n​Cedars “You’re My Neighbor!” art exh
 ibition runs from March 3 through April 12\, 2026
LOCATION:Toby's Feed Barn
URL:https://www.cedarslife.org/events
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Heather Mae & Flamy Grant
DTSTART;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260403T200000
DTEND;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260403T000000
UID:2602246392pGRnoEOLwUd3VqucUQ
DESCRIPTION:Heather Mae is an award-winning songwriter whose evocative voc
 als and rhythmic piano style creates intoxicating music that tackles compl
 ex topics surrounding mental health\, LGBTQ\\+ issues\, self-love\, racial
  injustice\, social inequality\, and women’s rights. Her newest project\
 , GLIMMER\, is a collection of nine songs supporting one central theme:”
  Feel To Heal.” Within the grooves of the new album\, Mae wrestles with 
 the complexities of existing as a human with mental illness. From her \\#M
 eToo-inspired feminist anthem “Warrior\,” featuring a choir of 100\\+ 
 female vocalists\, to “You Are My Favorite”\, a love song written for 
 her wife inspired by her own wedding vows which will surely be the 2019 we
 dding soundtrack for LGBTQ\\+ couples\, Mae shows she’s nothing less tha
 n a powerhouse. She has examined her struggle with Bipolar Disorder from e
 very angle in order to create her most sonically adventurous set of record
 ings yet--and to remind us that we aren’t alone.
LOCATION:HopMonk Tavern Novato
URL:https://www.bandsintown.com/e/1037928675?app_id=pkvts0on0m&came_from=2
 87&utm_medium=api&utm_source=partner_api&utm_campaign=event
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:John Doe
DTSTART;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260403T190000
DTEND;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260403T000000
UID:2602245tnEdK0m80yeZLtYwxSHuA
DESCRIPTION:John Doe was born in 1977 when he arrived in Los Angeles. His 
 previous life in Tennessee\, Wisconsin & Baltimore was a great & fertile t
 ime but new music and social changes led him to events that created a life
  in art. He graduated from Antioch College in Baltimore in 1975\, worked a
 s a roofer\, aluminum siding mechanic\, and ran a poetry reading series. M
 s. Meyers was his landlord in the rural black community of Simpsonville \,
  MD.\n\nJohn met Exene Cervenka at the Venice poetry workshop Nov 1976 and
  he started working with Billy Zoom around the same time. When DJ Bonebrak
 e joined X in mid-1977 the line up was complete. They released six studio 
 records\, five or six singles and one live record from 1978-1993. Five of 
 X’s records have been re-issued along with two compilations. The Unheard
  Music documents their lives and progress as a band from 1980-83. In 2009 
 the film was included in the Sundance UCLA Archive of greatest films of al
 l time. They appeared several times on American Bandstand\, Solid Gold and
  David Letterman. As one of the last original punk rock bands standing\, t
 hey continue to tour. The day that X played a free noontime concert in Ful
 lerton\, CA\, they caused Orange County’s greatest high school truancy r
 ate to date.\n\nIn 1988 John started a family and lived in the Tehachapi M
 ountains\, near the “Grapevine” of Highway 5\, which separates souther
 n and central California. He has recorded 8 solo records w/ numerous renow
 ned singers and players\, more recently including Patty Griffin\, Dan Auer
 bach\, Aimee Mann\, Don Was\, Kathleen Edwards and Greg Liesz. He has appe
 ared in over 50 films and television productions\, with some of his most n
 otable roles in Road House\, Georgia\, Roadside Prophets\, Great Balls of 
 Fire\, Pure Country and Roswell. He continues to act these days but more s
 poradically as his touring schedule has become more demanding.\n\nOther mu
 sical side projects include work with the Knitters\, Jill Sobule and The S
 adies. He continues to write poetry and has even taught workshops from tim
 e to time. He currently lives in Austin\, TX.
LOCATION:HopMonk Tavern
URL:https://www.bandsintown.com/e/107657374?app_id=pkvts0on0m&came_from=28
 7&utm_medium=api&utm_source=partner_api&utm_campaign=event
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:T-Bone N Weasel - Live Theatre at THE 222 / Healdsburg
DTSTART;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260403T190000
DTEND;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260403T190000
UID:260219ujABU67ffkaeM3v47XvFZQ
DESCRIPTION:**T**he play follows the antic peregrinations of two ex-convic
 ts as they make their erratic way across South Carolina in search of a hot
  meal or an easy mark.\n\nHoping to bring themselves up to at least the po
 verty level\, two ex-convicts\, T Bone (who is Black) and Weasel (who is W
 hite) have stolen a rather decrepit Buick and have set off across South Ca
 rolina with minor mayhem in mind. Moving swiftly from one adventure to an
 other\, they botch an attempted robbery\,  are swindled out of the Buick 
 by a fast-talking used car dealer\, run afoul of a sexually voracious lady
  farmer\, fall into the clutches of a larcenous country preacher\, and try
  to make off with the automobile of a politically ambitious small town doc
 tor who wants to exhibit them as examples of what poverty can do to people
 . Then it is back on the road again…\n\n*Every time they try to break th
 e law\, the law breaks them. A tale of two idiots\, smartly told by playwr
 ight Jon Klein\, “T-Bone n Weasel” is kind of like a good road-kill: i
 t’s funny\, gross and makes a lasting impression.* — Variety\n\nFeatur
 ing:\n\nT-Bone – Aldo Billingslea\n\nWeasel – Timothy Redman\n\nVerna 
 Mae – Sylvia Burboeck\n\n***Sponsored by Linda Hillel & Jon Eisenberg an
 d Malin Giddings & Richard Hechler***\n\nTheatre - Programmed by Aldo Bill
 ingslea and Amy Kossow\n\nTHE 222 / 222 Healdsburg Avenue / Healdsburg CA
LOCATION:THE 222 / Healdsburg
URL:https://the222.org/product/t-bone-n-weasel/
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Adult Gymnastics Class
DTSTART;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260403T170000
DTEND;TZID=PDT;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260403T183000
UID:2602144eKbamAubk62O8omCY7qOw
DESCRIPTION:**We’re offering Adult Gymnastics Classes for the 18+ crowd!
 **\n\n**Adult Gymnastics classes occur every Tuesday 5:00 PM to 6:30 PM &
  Friday from 6:30 PM to 8:00 PM.**\n\n**$20 per person\, OR pay for a wh
 ole 8-week session in advance through our site. You can attend on Tuesday\
 , Friday\, or both!**\n\n**Please bring the class fee in cash at the time 
 of arrival. This can be a DROP IN\, so there is no need to sign up online 
 before coming!**\n\nIf you’ve ever wanted to try out gymnastics or get b
 ack into it in adulthood\, now is your chance! During our adult classes\, 
 open to all genders\, our coaches will move at the pace of each student\, 
 helping them achieve goals they set for themselves. **No experience is ne
 cessary** to be involved in this class\, so this is a great opportunity t
 o learn the basics and get some exercise\, no matter what age you are! Try
  out our trampoline\, bars\, beam\, and other gym equipment in a safe and 
 supportive environment. You can build strength and increase your range of 
 motion while having fun like you’re a kid again.\n\nAsk our coaches what
  you can work on between classes\, and they’ll help personalize your tra
 ining!\n\nPlease wear something comfortable and keep long hair tied back. 
 Skirts and restrictive clothing are not recommended. You must remove your 
 shoes before going onto the mat or using equipment. Please let us know if 
 you have any physical limitations or health conditions that may interfere 
 with doing certain motions. We recommend bringing a water bottle.\n\nYou c
 an email us for more info or join our mailing list at: info@sonomagymnast
 icsacademy.com
LOCATION:Sonoma Gymnastics Academy
URL:https://sonomagymnasticsacademy.com/home/adult-gymnastics-night/
X-SOURCE:Press Democrat
END:VEVENT
